n. Even in many urban areas, households provide at least a proportion of their own food needs. This access to land and subsistence crops sets the Pacific apart from most of the developing world where access to land and subsistence crops is often much less widespread. C.4. Poverty line estimation I) Derivation of the food basket for the FPL 35. For the HIES 2006 and HIES 2010, an expenditure-based method has been used to calculate the basic food baskets and the corresponding food poverty lines. As discussed above, separate estimates were made for Port Vila, Luganville and Rural (other islands/rural). The expenditure-based food baskets were derived from the type of food and expenditure patterns of the poor (households with p.c.a.e. in the lowest 3 deciles), as reported by households. The food items (from purchases, household production, and transfers to and from households as gifts) were then weighted by expenditure shares and quantities. The first 30 or so items, with the highest weighted expenditure and covering approximately 80-85% of all food expenditure, formed the food basket used in the estimation of the FPL. The FPL has an absolute base (2,100 kilocalories/ day) but the items that make up those calories are derived from actual consumption patterns in each of the three areas; Figures 4.a, 4.b and 4.c illustrate. Vanuatu Hardship & Poverty Report 2012 31 Bananas (Cooking) Rice Island Taro/Taro Fiji Manioc Yam Island Cabbage Kumala dry Coconut/Copra Water Taro Mangoes Bread (sliced, loaf, square, rolls, .. Other fish Chicken/Local chicken Tinned tuna Laplap (Yam, banana, manioc, etc...) Sugar Watermelon & Rock melon Breadfruit Cabin Biscuits Other Tinned fish Crabs Pineapples Corn Beef fresh Pawpaws Top 25 Food Items for Rural L3D HH 0 2 4 6 8 10 12 % of food consumed Figures 4.a, 4.b and 4.c: Food baskets of the bottom three expenditure deciles 0 2 4 6 8 10 12 Rice Bread (sliced, loaf, square, rolls, French) Island Cabbage Chicken (chicken parts) Manioc Tinned T